          "body": "The scribal machinery of the Persian empire springs into action on the twenty-third of Sivan (8:9), seventy days after Haman's decree (cf. 3:12). The chapter's most detailed section deliberately mirrors chapter 3:12-15 — same scribes, same signet ring, same 127 provinces, same multilingual distribution, same horse-mounted couriers. The content of the counter-edict (8:11) echoes the language of 3:13 with the subject and object reversed: where Haman authorized the peoples to destroy the Jews, Mordecai authorizes the Jews to assemble and destroy any armed force that attacks them. The Jews' right to plunder their attackers' spoil (8:11) is especially significant — it is the mirror image of what Haman promised the peoples in 3:13. One interpretive question that has occupied commentators is why women and children of the enemies are named in 8:11. The most defensible reading is that this language mirrors Haman's original edict verbatim (3:13) — the counter-decree does not authorize aggressive massacre but frames a full legal defense against whatever the enemies bring, including the full force Haman's decree authorized against the Jews."
