        "excerpt": "For a decree which is written in the name of the king and sealed with the king's signet ring may not be revoked.",
        "body": "The first movement of the chapter resolves a legal problem that the dramatic climax of chapter 7 — Haman's execution — left entirely untouched. Readers who have followed the narrative since 3:12-13 understand that Haman's death decree carries the king's own seal. Persian law, as reflected in both Esther (1:19; 8:8) and Daniel (6:8, 12, 15), operated under the principle of irrevocability. The king himself cannot annul what the king has decreed. Haman is dead, but the empire still counts down to the thirteenth of Adar.\n\nThis legal reality explains Esther's second petition (8:3-6) and distinguishes it from the first (7:3-4). The first petition was personal: she asked for her own life and the life of her people. The second is structural: she asks for the legal machinery to be turned around. She approaches the throne a second time without summons — the same mortal risk she took in chapter 5 (cf. 4:11) — weeping and prostrate at the king's feet (8:3). The repeated extension of the golden scepter (8:4) confirms that Esther's access to the king is not exhausted by the first crisis; favor is renewable.\n\nHer fourfold conditional petition (8:5) is not diplomatic padding. Each conditional clause — \"if it pleases the king,\" \"if I have found favor,\" \"if the matter seems proper,\" \"if I am pleasing in his sight\" — positions her appeal entirely within the realm of the king's sovereign goodwill. She makes no claim. She offers no argument from justice. She argues from personal relationship and royal pleasure — the same posture of dependence that has characterized her throughout the book. As Karen Jobes (NIVAC, *Esther*) observes, Esther's rhetorical strategy consistently refuses to demand what only the king can give.\n\nThe king's response in verses 7-8 is at once a recital of accomplished facts and a delegation of extraordinary authority. He does not — because he cannot — cancel Haman's decree. Instead, he hands the signet ring to Mordecai and authorizes him to write in the king's own name. The legal irrevocability of the first decree becomes the legal mechanism of the second: because a sealed royal decree cannot be undone, a new sealed royal decree can counter-act it permanently. God does not work by canceling the structures of the world; He works through them.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tabbaat* (signet ring) traces the book's power arc: given to Haman in 3:10, recovered and given to Mordecai in 8:2 and 8:10. *Katav* (write) appears eight times in this chapter alone — the act of writing is the chapter's central verb. *Dat* (decree/law) — the irrevocable Persian legal order that both traps and ultimately delivers."
