        "excerpt": "Then Mordecai went out from the presence of the king in royal robes of blue and white, with a large crown of gold and a garment of fine linen and purple; and the city of Susa shouted and rejoiced.",
        "body": "Verse 15 is the book's visual climax. Mordecai's exit from the palace is staged as a deliberate inversion of 4:1-2 — the only other description of Mordecai in the public space of Susa. In chapter 4 he wore torn garments and sackcloth, covered his head with ashes, and wailed aloud (4:1). Now he exits wearing royal blue and white (*tekhelet v'chur*), with a large golden crown (*atarah*), and a purple garment of fine linen (*buts*). The colors are precisely those of the Persian royal court (cf. 1:6) and of the tabernacle appointments (Exodus 26:1, 31, 36) — both registers elevate what Mordecai now represents.\n\nThe city's response is equally deliberate: Susa \"shouted\" (*tsahal*, a shout of exultation) and \"rejoiced\" (*samach*). In 3:15, when the first decree went out, \"the city of Susa was in confusion\" — the same city, now rejoicing. The royal capital's emotional register has inverted entirely. The reversal is not private; it is publicly enacted in the streets of the empire's capital.\n\nVerse 16 then supplies the theological summary of the chapter in four Hebrew words: *orah v'simchah v'sasvon viyqar* — light, gladness, joy, honor. This fourfold description is the deliberate inversion of the fourfold mourning of 4:1-3: torn garments, sackcloth, ashes, fasting, weeping, wailing. Tim Keller, writing on this passage, notes that the book of Esther stages the Christian pattern of reversal — what begins in loss ends in vindication — not as a theology lesson but as a historical narrative that the whole canon trains us to read as pointing forward to the ultimate reversal at the resurrection. The word *orah* (light) carries the heaviest theological freight: in Isaiah 9:2 and 60:1, it is the word for the dawn of salvation in a world under shadow. The narrator places it first in the fourfold list, as the foundational quality from which gladness, joy, and honor flow.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Orah* (light, 8:16) — used for salvation-light in Psalm 27:1; Isaiah 9:2; Micah 7:8-9. *Simchah* (gladness) and *sasvon* (joy/exultation) — a near-synonymous pair for festive celebration; both recur in Esther 9:17-19 describing the Purim institution. *Yeqar* (honor) — the same word used of the honor Haman wanted for himself (6:6-11) and which now belongs to Mordecai."
